VIRAL GASTROENTERITIS UPDATE 2002 - UK & IRELAND (04)
*****************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[The outbreaks of viral gastroenteritis included in these updates have the
characteristics of "winter vomiting disease", and are presumed to be caused
by Norwalk-like viruses (caliciviruses classified in the genus
_Norovirus_), although this is rarely confirmed microbiologically. The UK
and Ireland seem to be particularly prone at present to outbreaks of
"winter-vomiting" disease in institutional settings. - Mod.CP]
In these updates:
[1] England (Kettering & Northampton)
[2] Scotland (Glasgow)
[3] Scotland (Lanarkshire)
******
[1]
Date: Wed 6 Nov 2002
From: "Banks, A-Lan" <A-Lan.Banks@derwent.co.uk>
Source: Northampton Chronicle and Echo (News Online), Tue 5 Nov 2002 [edited]
<http://www.northantsnew.co.uk/ref/news_chron.asp?ID=13734>

Viral gastroenteritis outbreaks at hospitals in Kettering and Northampton
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Winter vomiting illness has wiped out waiting list operations in Kettering
in the past month and now the first cases have been confirmed at
Northampton General [Hospital]. Family and friends of patients in
Northampton have been told to stay away or only visit for short periods if
necessary, to limit further infection.
A spokeswoman for Northampton General Hospital said: "We have had some
cases of the winter vomiting disease virus but we are not in an outbreak
situation because so far they have been sporadic. "Infection control has
been increased and restrictions have been placed on visiting times."
This week Kettering General [Hospital] continues to turn away waiting list
patients because staff and patients are still falling ill. However the
number of new cases diagnosed is gradually dropping.
Last year winter vomiting illness shut down several hospitals in Scotland
as it spread through staff and patients. The virus can reach huge amounts
of people once it is inside a hospital. Symptoms take a few days to
manifest so visitors bring it in from the community, as do staff. Patients
are always more vulnerable to infection and many arrive with one complaint
and quickly pick up the virus. Hygiene rules like always washing hands and
wearing gloves and disposable aprons are reinforced to prevent cross infection.
(byline: Perrie Balthazar)
--
Banks, A-Lan
<A-Lan.Banks@derwent.co.uk>
